==Old English==
===Etymology===
From an Indo-European root ''*bhrūg-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''brūka'', Old High German ''brūhhan'' (German [[brauchen]]), Old Saxon ''brūkan'' (Dutch [[bruiken]]), Gothic [[𐌱𐍂𐌿𐌺𐌾𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root was also the source of Latin [[frui]] ‘enjoy’ and [[frux]] ‘fruit’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'bru:can/

===Verb===
'''brūcan''' (strong verb class II: '''brȳcþ''' ‘he enjoys’; '''brēac''' ‘he enjoyed’; '''brucon''' ‘they enjoyed’; '''ġebrocen''' past participle)
# to [[enjoy]], to make use of
# to [[digest]] food

